Forward Learning via Reverse Construction (FLRC) — Pantheon Operational Form

Core Idea

A system improves its ability to act in the present by:
	1.	Learning transition dynamics from past observations
	2.	Imagining candidate future states
	3.	Tracing feasible paths back from those futures to the present
	4.	Choosing the lowest-cost / most reversible path

This merges prediction, planning, and optimization.

⸻

Formal Structure

Let:
	•	S₀ = current system state
	•	Sₚ = past states
	•	S_f = candidate future states
	•	D(x) = inferred system dynamics
	•	C(path) = cost / resistance function

Step 1 — Dynamics Learning

From historical transitions:

S_p \rightarrow D(x)

This is pattern extraction.

Pantheon modules involved:
	•	Raven → pattern compression
	•	Spider → relationship mapping
	•	Mirror → invariant validation

⸻

Step 2 — Candidate Future Generation

Generate possible future states:

S_0 \rightarrow S_f

Examples depending on domain:
	•	profitable market regime
	•	scientific discovery
	•	improved system architecture
	•	social coordination outcome

⸻

Step 3 — Reverse Path Construction

For each candidate future:

S_f \rightarrow S_0

Search for feasible paths connecting them.

This resembles:
	•	dynamic programming
	•	reinforcement learning planning
	•	heuristic search

⸻

Step 4 — Minimum Resistance Selection

Choose:

P^* = \arg\min C(P)

Where cost includes:
	•	risk
	•	time
	•	resource expenditure
	•	irreversibility

This step directly interfaces with Pantheon governance:

Module	Role
Badger (CAO)	protects attention allocation
Reversibility Gate	prevents irreversible paths
Goblin Financier	optimizes resource allocation
Checksum	integrity verification


